<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>Homework 04</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Instructions:</alert> Complete all the exercises below and submit your work via 
      <url href="https://www.gradescope.com/courses/1238540">Gradescope</url> by Monday February 23 at 10pm.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Let <m>f,g\colon X\to Y</m> be two continuous functions.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that
            <md>
              <mrow>f\times g\colon X\times X \amp \longrightarrow Y\times Y</mrow>
              <mrow>(x,x') \amp \longmapsto (f(x),g(x'))</mrow>
            </md>
            is continuous.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that the diagonal map
            <md>
              <mrow>\Delta\colon Y \amp \longrightarrow Y\times Y </mrow>
              <mrow>y \amp \longmapsto (y,y) </mrow>
            </md>
            is continuous.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose that <m>Y</m> separates points. Prove that
            <md>
              \{x\in X\mid f(x)=g(x)\}
            </md>
            is closed.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>X</m> separates points if and only if
            <md>
              \{(x,x)\mid x\in X\}\subseteq X\times X
            </md>
            is closed (with respect to the product topology on <m>X\times X</m>).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
              Prove that the line with two origins <m>\mathbb R\amalg_{\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}}\mathbb R</m> 
              does not separate points. You might proceed in the following fashion: let <m>0_+,0_-</m> denote the 
              two origins. Let <m>U_{\pm}</m> denote open neighborhoods of <m>0_{\pm}</m>, respectively. Construct the 
              canonical continuous function <m>\mathbb R\amalg_{\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}}\mathbb R\to \mathbb R</m> 
              and use it to show that <m>U_+\cap U_-</m> is nonempty.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>i\colon S^1\hookrightarrow D^2</m> denote the continuous inclusion of <m>S^1</m> as the boundary of 
              <m>D^2</m>. Let <m>P</m> denote the pushout of
              <md>
                S^1\times D^2\xleftarrow{\operatorname{id}_{S^1}\times i} S^1\times S^1
                \xrightarrow{i\times \operatorname{id}_{S^1}} D^2\times S^1.
              </md>
              Construct a continuous bijection <m>P\to S^3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              It will likely prove helpful to view <m>S^3</m> as a subspace of <m>\mathbb C^2\cong \mathbb R^4</m> and think 
              about functions like
              <md>
                <mrow>S^1\times D^2 \amp \longrightarrow S^3 </mrow>
                <mrow>(w,z) \amp \longmapsto \frac{(w,z)}{\sqrt{1+|z|^2}}. </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Recall that a <term>partially ordered set</term> (or <term>poset</term>) <m>(P,\le)</m> is a set <m>P</m> equipped 
          with a reflexive, antisymmetric, transitive binary relation <m>\le</m>. Given a poset <m>(P,\le)</m>, let <m>\tau_{\le}</m> 
          denote the collection of subsets of <m>P</m> that are <term>upwards closed</term>, that is, <m>U\in \tau_{\le}</m> :iff 
          <m>x\in U</m> and <m>x\le y\in P</m> implies <m>y\in U</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>(P,\tau_{\le})</m> is a topological space. (This is called the <term>poset</term> or 
            <term>Alexandrov topology</term> on <m>P</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that the poset topology on <m>P</m> is generated by the basis of <term>principal up-sets</term>: subsets 
            of <m>P</m> of the form
            <md>
              x^{\uparrow} := \{y\in P\mid x\le y\}.
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give necessary and sufficient conditions on a poset <m>P</m> that ensure its poset topology separates points.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
